WEBVTT

00:00.876 --> 00:02.418
<i> - For two seasons,</i>

00:02.461 --> 00:03.961
<i> America's most talented</i>
<i> bladesmiths</i>

00:04.005 --> 00:05.421
<i> have faced off</i>
<i> in the ultimate competition...</i>

00:05.464 --> 00:07.297
- Gettin' pretty hot
in the kitchen.

00:07.341 --> 00:10.300
<i> - Making some of history's</i>
<i> deadliest weapons.</i>

00:10.344 --> 00:12.261
<i> Now, with the stakes higher</i>
<i> than ever,</i>

00:12.304 --> 00:14.346
<i> a new batch of bladesmiths</i>
<i> enter the Forge</i>

00:14.390 --> 00:15.806
<i> to test their skills.</i>

00:15.850 --> 00:17.057
- W-whoa, watch out, watch out,
watch out!

00:17.101 --> 00:18.934
[machines whirring,
blade slicing]

00:18.978 --> 00:21.020
<i> - Only one will take home</i>
<i> $10,000</i>

00:21.063 --> 00:22.563
- Whoo!
<i> - And be crowned</i>

00:22.606 --> 00:25.399
<i> "Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

00:25.443 --> 00:28.318
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

00:28.362 --> 00:36.160
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:36.203 --> 00:37.870
<i> - My name's Harry Black.</i>

00:37.913 --> 00:41.248
and I've been a bladesmith
for about 30 years.

00:41.292 --> 00:44.752
<i> I am also a blacksmith,</i>
<i> a silversmith,</i>

00:44.795 --> 00:47.004
and I am
a professional Santa Claus.

00:47.048 --> 00:49.590
<i> [Christmas music]</i>

00:49.633 --> 00:52.051
<i> - My name's Emiliano Carrillo.</i>
<i> I'm 21.</i>

00:52.094 --> 00:53.844
<i> Being a bladesmith at 21,</i>

00:53.888 --> 00:56.138
it's really easy to get counted
out by the older smiths.

00:56.182 --> 00:59.183
<i> But I think being younger is</i>
<i> gonna give me</i>

00:59.226 --> 01:00.309
<i> a bit of an upper hand.</i>

01:00.352 --> 01:02.561
<i> - My name is Jay Replogle.</i>

01:02.605 --> 01:05.230
Ever since I was a kid,
kung fu fighting my brother,

01:05.274 --> 01:07.024
you know,
with sticks in the backyard,

01:07.068 --> 01:08.984
<i> I've always had a fascination</i>
<i> with knives,</i>

01:09.028 --> 01:13.697
and bladesmithing is just the
mature level of that, I guess.

01:13.741 --> 01:15.532
<i> - My name is Stephan Fowler.</i>

01:15.576 --> 01:18.327
<i> I am 36 years old,</i>
<i>and I am from Atlanta, Georgia.</i>

01:18.370 --> 01:20.579
My favorite part
of making a blade is

01:20.623 --> 01:23.290
at the end of the day
actually holding and being able

01:23.334 --> 01:25.667
to admire the product
of your day's effort.

01:25.711 --> 01:27.461
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:27.505 --> 01:30.005
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:30.049 --> 01:33.967
In this arena, every aspect of
your blade-making capabilities

01:34.011 --> 01:35.344
will be tested.

01:35.387 --> 01:38.472
Construction, execution,
performance:

01:38.516 --> 01:39.973
these are just some
of the details

01:40.017 --> 01:41.225
that our judges will be
evaluating.

01:41.268 --> 01:43.102
Let's meet them now.

01:43.145 --> 01:46.897
World-renowned knife-maker
Jason Knight.

01:46.941 --> 01:50.275
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker.

01:50.319 --> 01:52.069
World-renowned
Kali martial artist

01:52.113 --> 01:54.238
Doug Marcaida.

01:54.281 --> 01:55.656
All right, gentlemen.
In front of you

01:55.699 --> 01:57.032
on your anvils,
there's a cloth.

01:57.076 --> 01:58.325
Please remove it.

01:58.369 --> 02:00.744
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:00.788 --> 02:02.704
In this first round,
you will have to forge weld

02:02.748 --> 02:04.623
those cubes of steel together

02:04.667 --> 02:06.959
to make a billet from which
you will make your blades.

02:07.002 --> 02:09.461
But that's not the only wrinkle.

02:09.505 --> 02:15.134
The blades that you forge
must be for friction folders.

02:15.177 --> 02:18.095
- A friction folder is more
of a primitive folding knife.

02:18.139 --> 02:21.014
<i> There's just a pin</i>
<i> that forms a hinge,</i>

02:21.058 --> 02:24.434
<i> and the tail on the back is</i>
<i> supported by the hand,</i>

02:24.478 --> 02:28.313
<i> and allows you to cut without</i>
<i> it closing on your hand.</i>

02:28.357 --> 02:30.274
And it's gonna be
kind of difficult

02:30.317 --> 02:31.942
getting all that done, you know,
within the time.

02:31.986 --> 02:33.610
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:33.654 --> 02:36.071
- After round two,
your finished folders will

02:36.115 --> 02:39.575
then be tested in a ham slice

02:39.618 --> 02:41.702
<i> and splitting a dowel.</i>

02:41.745 --> 02:44.163
You will have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

02:44.206 --> 02:46.874
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:46.917 --> 02:49.084
Good luck, bladesmiths.

02:49.128 --> 02:52.671
Your ten-minute design window
starts...

02:52.715 --> 02:53.714
now.

02:53.757 --> 02:55.716
<i> [rock music]</i>

02:55.759 --> 02:58.051
- And they don't have to use
all those cubes.

02:58.095 --> 03:00.220
- I would use all of the cubes,

03:00.264 --> 03:02.264
but I don't want to say
how I would do it,

03:02.308 --> 03:03.432
because they might hear me.

03:03.475 --> 03:05.184
- [laughs]

03:05.227 --> 03:08.187
- I've never made
a friction folder before,

03:08.230 --> 03:11.732
<i> let alone</i>
<i> out of little cubes of steel.</i>

03:11.775 --> 03:15.277
My design I had in mind was
just a basic utility knife.

03:15.321 --> 03:16.945
<i>You know, just very simplistic,</i>

03:16.989 --> 03:18.655
<i> something that works</i>

03:18.699 --> 03:20.657
<i> and does a good job</i>
<i> at what it does.</i>

03:20.701 --> 03:22.951
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:22.995 --> 03:24.369
<i> - I think I'm going to make</i>

03:24.413 --> 03:26.914
a kind of Scandinavian-style
friction folder.

03:26.957 --> 03:30.042
<i> When I was younger, my parents</i>
<i> read me "Lord of the Rings,"</i>

03:30.085 --> 03:31.793
<i> and so when I was finally able</i>

03:31.837 --> 03:34.004
<i> to actually start forging</i>
<i> knives and swords,</i>

03:34.048 --> 03:36.590
<i> all these fantastic things</i>
<i> that I had read about,</i>

03:36.634 --> 03:38.634
I could finally actually bring
into life.

03:38.677 --> 03:40.802
<i> I've only made</i>
<i> one friction folder before,</i>

03:40.846 --> 03:42.596
and it was
probably about that big,

03:42.640 --> 03:46.350
<i> so, going in,</i>
<i> I'm pretty nervous.</i>

03:46.393 --> 03:50.354
- I'm kind of leaning
towards a southwestern bowie.

03:50.397 --> 03:53.357
<i> They tended to have</i>
<i> a very thick spine,</i>

03:53.400 --> 03:55.400
<i> a very pronounced point.</i>

03:55.444 --> 03:57.194
<i> Creating a knife is</i>

03:57.238 --> 03:59.321
<i> not unlike a mother</i>
<i> giving birth to a child.</i>

03:59.365 --> 04:02.324
There's this thing
that wasn't there,

04:02.368 --> 04:03.825
<i> and here it is.</i>

04:03.869 --> 04:05.869
This is what I made.
This is my baby.

04:05.913 --> 04:08.080
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:08.123 --> 04:11.500
<i> - I am drawing</i>
<i> more of a seax blade,</i>

04:11.543 --> 04:15.254
<i> because I'm hoping</i>
<i> that the design will be good</i>

04:15.297 --> 04:18.298
<i> for hacking and cutting.</i>

04:18.342 --> 04:21.343
I've been a Santa Claus
for 35 years.

04:21.387 --> 04:22.928
<i> I love it.</i>

04:22.972 --> 04:25.597
And I do give coal
for Christmas.

04:25.641 --> 04:27.224
- All right, bladesmiths,

04:27.268 --> 04:28.976
your ten-minute design window
has closed.

04:29.019 --> 04:31.520
Your three-hour forging time
starts...

04:31.563 --> 04:33.397
now!

04:33.440 --> 04:36.316
It has begun!

04:36.360 --> 04:39.444
How are they gonna forge weld
all those little cubes together?

04:39.488 --> 04:41.780
- What they should do is

04:41.824 --> 04:43.156
stack them all up--

04:43.200 --> 04:45.242
we got a great welder
over there.

04:45.286 --> 04:47.369
Weld the pieces
all the way closed.

04:47.413 --> 04:49.246
Now you have a solid chunk
of steel.

04:49.290 --> 04:51.039
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:51.083 --> 04:53.208
<i> - I'm intrigued</i>
<i> by this challenge.</i>

04:53.252 --> 04:55.877
Putting pieces of steel together
into a single bar

04:55.921 --> 04:57.629
is just like I'm
putting back together a tomato

04:57.673 --> 04:59.381
before I make tomato sauce.

04:59.425 --> 05:03.010
- If these guys don't get
those cubes cleaned up

05:03.053 --> 05:04.303
and welded together well,

05:04.346 --> 05:05.721
what will happen when they start

05:05.764 --> 05:07.139
to forge out their billet?

05:07.182 --> 05:10.058
- You get voids or cold shuts,

05:10.102 --> 05:11.643
flux trapped in between
the layers.

05:11.687 --> 05:13.729
You don't want that.

05:13.772 --> 05:16.106
You're just trying to get
that flux evenly distributed,

05:16.150 --> 05:18.608
just trying to make sure
everything's nice and clean.

05:18.652 --> 05:22.362
Cleanliness is godliness
with a forge weld.

05:22.406 --> 05:25.824
- Flux is just there to keep
the steel where you're welding

05:25.868 --> 05:27.868
from oxidizing.

05:27.911 --> 05:30.662
- When you use it, oxygen's
not able to get to the surface

05:30.706 --> 05:32.497
to form that scale,

05:32.541 --> 05:35.459
and when you forge weld,
all the flux will squirt out...

05:35.502 --> 05:37.085
you hope.

05:37.129 --> 05:38.754
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:38.797 --> 05:40.964
- I noticed
that Harry and Emiliano

05:41.008 --> 05:44.134
instantly went over
to the MIG welders

05:44.178 --> 05:46.511
and started welding cubes
together.

05:46.555 --> 05:50.390
- Going in, my plan is to weld
this together very quickly.

05:50.434 --> 05:53.852
<i> The material doesn't</i>
<i> really help me in this case,</i>

05:53.896 --> 05:56.480
because instead of having
a big chunk to work from,

05:56.523 --> 05:58.815
it's tons of tiny chunks that I
have to turn into a big one.

05:58.859 --> 06:01.943
<i> So the welds are</i>
<i> the kind of scariest part.</i>

06:01.987 --> 06:04.988
As long as that goes well,
the rest should go smoothly.

06:05.032 --> 06:06.156
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:06.200 --> 06:07.741
<i> - I would like to believe</i>

06:07.785 --> 06:10.702
that forge welding is
a strong suit of mine,

06:10.746 --> 06:14.539
because I've been doing it
for a long time.

06:14.583 --> 06:17.959
My concerns would be making sure
I get a good, strong weld

06:18.003 --> 06:19.795
to begin with.

06:19.838 --> 06:22.422
<i> What makes me believe</i>
<i> that I can win this is</i>

06:22.466 --> 06:26.968
I have a lot of experience,
and...

06:27.012 --> 06:28.929
I'm handsome.

06:28.972 --> 06:31.556
You know what the hottest thing
in the blacksmith shop is?

06:33.977 --> 06:35.727
<i> - I'm the only one</i>
<i> in the group</i>

06:35.771 --> 06:38.105
<i> who's never made</i>
<i> a friction folder before.</i>

06:38.148 --> 06:40.565
<i>I'm having to engineer as I go.</i>

06:40.609 --> 06:44.569
- Jay over here put all cubes
one by one into the forge.

06:44.613 --> 06:47.656
- Dave, your face just now was
like, "I don't understand that."

06:47.699 --> 06:49.032
[metallic clinking]

06:49.076 --> 06:50.492
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:50.536 --> 06:52.869
- My plan is
to get my steel heated,

06:52.913 --> 06:55.580
and I'm gonna flatten it
into little pancakes.

06:55.624 --> 06:57.874
<i> It's sort of like</i>
<i> what the Japanese do</i>

06:57.918 --> 06:59.126
with their metal.

06:59.169 --> 07:00.836
<i> They'll get a bloom of steel,</i>

07:00.879 --> 07:02.337
and they'll flatten it
into little pancakes,

07:02.381 --> 07:04.423
and then they stack up
the little pancakes.

07:04.466 --> 07:07.008
- Going this way is, um--

07:07.052 --> 07:08.885
it's like the longest way
around.

07:08.929 --> 07:11.763
[metallic clinking]

07:14.768 --> 07:16.226
- One hour has elapsed!

07:16.270 --> 07:18.395
You have only two hours
remaining

07:18.439 --> 07:20.188
to finish your work!

07:20.232 --> 07:23.150
- Oh, thank God for kilts.

07:23.193 --> 07:24.985
I would not want
to be wearing jeans right now.

07:25.028 --> 07:26.611
<i> I've got to pick up some time.</i>

07:26.655 --> 07:28.196
<i> This is my chance.</i>

07:28.240 --> 07:30.782
This is where I shine.
I can forge.

07:30.826 --> 07:33.034
<i> The big hammers, you can</i>
<i>really get yourself in trouble,</i>

07:33.078 --> 07:35.203
because they put big marks
in steel.

07:35.247 --> 07:36.955
<i> But if you know</i>
<i> how to control them,</i>

07:36.999 --> 07:39.499
they put big marks in steel
right where you want them.

07:39.543 --> 07:41.543
♪ La da-dun-dun-dun ♪

07:41.587 --> 07:44.004
- Ha!
Yeah, he's an opera singer.

07:44.047 --> 07:46.548
- ♪ What you gonna do? ♪

07:46.592 --> 07:48.216
Glorious!

07:48.260 --> 07:49.634
- He's just having
a conversation

07:49.678 --> 07:50.844
with himself over there.

07:50.888 --> 07:52.345
I don't know
who he's talking to.

07:52.389 --> 07:53.638
I don't know
who he's yelling at.

07:53.682 --> 07:56.683
- ♪ Mm-lapa mm-lapa ♪
Heat up!

07:56.727 --> 07:59.478
Stop staring into the forge,
Stephan.

07:59.521 --> 08:01.229
It's fascinating.
It's fire.

08:01.273 --> 08:03.607
But don't stare in the forge.

08:03.650 --> 08:05.859
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:05.903 --> 08:08.945
- Big blue is being a little
rough on Emiliano over there.

08:08.989 --> 08:11.656
<i> - When I take my billet</i>
<i> to the power hammer</i>

08:11.700 --> 08:12.866
and start drawing it out,

08:12.910 --> 08:14.075
<i> I realize that there are</i>

08:14.119 --> 08:16.161
<i> little cracks that are there.</i>

08:16.205 --> 08:18.330
<i> There's no way I can actually</i>
<i> bring them back together</i>

08:18.373 --> 08:20.916
with the amount of material
that I have.

08:20.959 --> 08:22.667
<i> It's probably not</i>
<i> the best choice,</i>

08:22.711 --> 08:24.169
<i> but I'll keep going</i>

08:24.213 --> 08:26.671
and hope that I can fix them
in the grind.

08:26.715 --> 08:30.091
So, a little behind schedule,
but I think we can make it.

08:30.135 --> 08:31.885
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:31.929 --> 08:34.888
- I noticed, after hammering,

08:34.932 --> 08:39.976
that all of my welds
are not set.

08:40.020 --> 08:42.646
- Harry looks like he's having
some weld issues.

08:42.689 --> 08:44.898
He put his blocks together
in a long billet

08:44.942 --> 08:46.525
and he drew it out,

08:46.568 --> 08:48.818
but he never really
compressed it this way.

08:48.862 --> 08:54.324
- I have a gap
in the billet itself.

08:54.368 --> 08:56.826
<i> I can't believe this.</i>

08:56.870 --> 08:59.287
- I'm a little bit worried
about Harry.

08:59.331 --> 09:03.291
- If I am not able
to set the weld,

09:03.335 --> 09:05.627
it might be me going home.

09:05.671 --> 09:06.628
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:06.672 --> 09:08.296
Ah, crap.

09:08.340 --> 09:09.798
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:14.680 --> 09:15.971
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:16.014 --> 09:18.807
<i> - All of my welds are not set.</i>

09:18.850 --> 09:22.477
<i> If I am not able</i>
<i> to set the weld,</i>

09:22.521 --> 09:25.397
it might be me going home.

09:25.440 --> 09:28.608
- Is he chasing the problem
rather to just chop the area

09:28.652 --> 09:30.235
that he's having problems with?

09:30.279 --> 09:31.736
'Cause he doesn't need
all that metal.

09:31.780 --> 09:36.491
<i> - I'm going to cut</i>
<i> that section,</i>

09:36.535 --> 09:38.201
<i> fold it back on itself,</i>

09:38.245 --> 09:42.706
and continue to weld
to make it a solid piece.

09:42.749 --> 09:44.958
- 1 1/2 hours has elapsed!

09:45.002 --> 09:46.876
You have only 90 minutes
remaining

09:46.920 --> 09:48.003
to finish your work!

09:48.046 --> 09:50.547
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:50.591 --> 09:53.425
I know that Jay was a little bit
worried that he was behind.

09:53.468 --> 09:55.385
He's made a hell of a comeback.

09:55.429 --> 09:57.345
<i> - What I'm struggling with</i>
<i> the most right now is</i>

09:57.389 --> 10:00.098
I feel like I have
the weakest design.

10:00.142 --> 10:02.142
<i> Not ever having made</i>
<i> a friction folder,</i>

10:02.185 --> 10:06.104
I feel like I had to go
the very simplest route possible

10:06.148 --> 10:09.524
<i> for me to figure out all the</i>
<i> working parts on the fly.</i>

10:09.568 --> 10:11.484
- I think he's
maybe one of the smiths

10:11.528 --> 10:14.154
who's built a plan
and sticking to the plan

10:14.197 --> 10:16.906
and going--just muscling
right towards it.

10:16.950 --> 10:18.366
- This is crazy.

10:18.410 --> 10:22.203
- Yeah, right? It's hot.
- [laughing]

10:22.247 --> 10:24.289
<i> - I'm planning to bring</i>
<i> some blacksmith's elements</i>

10:24.333 --> 10:26.541
into the tang
to up the ante.

10:26.585 --> 10:28.418
I'm gonna put a scroll in it,

10:28.462 --> 10:31.087
which is gonna form
a nice backstop for your hand

10:31.131 --> 10:34.007
so you've got good, solid
pressure against the handle.

10:34.051 --> 10:37.552
I've got to be careful to do it
with some subtlety.

10:37.596 --> 10:40.472
- Stephan has actually
just forged a little curl

10:40.515 --> 10:42.140
into the tail of his blade.

10:42.184 --> 10:43.892
- He curled it upwards.

10:43.935 --> 10:45.977
I mean, that's gonna be awkward
to hold.

10:46.021 --> 10:49.105
If you want to show me something
I've never seen,

10:49.149 --> 10:51.107
don't do something
that's gonna get you eliminated.

10:51.151 --> 10:57.739
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:57.783 --> 10:59.866
- Emiliano's in the--
he's in the oil.

10:59.910 --> 11:00.867
He went for a quench.

11:00.911 --> 11:02.827
<i> - The heat treat was good,</i>

11:02.871 --> 11:05.455
<i> and now I'm gonna grind.</i>

11:05.499 --> 11:09.250
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:09.294 --> 11:11.086
[bleep].

11:11.129 --> 11:13.838
<i> - I realize</i>
<i> that there's a crack</i>

11:13.882 --> 11:15.757
<i> on the spine of the blade.</i>

11:15.801 --> 11:17.634
<i> It seems to be just aesthetic,</i>

11:17.678 --> 11:19.844
but I'm not sure.

11:19.888 --> 11:21.888
<i> But if I were to take a lot</i>
<i> of material off of the blade,</i>

11:21.932 --> 11:23.848
<i> I think it would disappear,</i>

11:23.892 --> 11:26.017
but I don't want to hand in
a blade that's too thin.

11:26.061 --> 11:28.269
<i> It's a hard decision,</i>

11:28.313 --> 11:30.397
<i> but I'm gonna leave it as-is.</i>

11:30.440 --> 11:33.149
- Anybody see
where Harry disappeared to?

11:33.193 --> 11:35.026
There he is.
He's over at the grinder.

11:35.070 --> 11:37.821
- He couldn't be very difficult
to find.

11:37.864 --> 11:39.364
- Santa Claus never gets seen.

11:39.408 --> 11:40.949
- [laughs]

11:40.992 --> 11:43.076
- Harry's blade looks
a lot better

11:43.120 --> 11:46.204
now that he's got his issues
worked out.

